|{{flag|France }}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canada<U+2013>France relations]], [[Embassy of France in Ottawa]], [[Embassy of Canada in Paris]], [[List of French ambassadors to Canada]], [[List of Canadian ambassadors to France]]

In the 2007 and 2008, French President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]<ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=079abc91-ed93-41c2-bce4-0579af73ea32&p=1 ]</ref>, Canadian Prime Minister [[Steven Harper]], and Quebec Premier [[Jean Charest]]<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=M1ARTM0013123 ]</ref> all spoke in favour of a Canada - EU free trade agreement.  In October 2008, Sarkozy became the first French President to address the [[National Assembly of Quebec]].  In his speech he spoke out against Quebec separatism, but recognized Quebec as a nation within Canada.  He said that, to France, Canada was a friend, and Quebec was family.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=079abc91-ed93-41c2-bce4-0579af73ea32&p=1 ]</ref>
