|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Saudi Arabia }}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canada<U+2013>Saudi Arabia relations]], [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia in Ottawa]]

Saudi Arabia is Canada's largest trade partner among the seven countries of the [[Arabian Peninsula]], totalling more than $2,000,000,000 in trade in 2005<ref name="dfait">{{cite web |date=2007-05-09|url = http://www.dfait-maeci.gc.ca/middle_east/saudi_arabia_relations-en.asp|title = CANADA-SAUDI ARABIA RELATIONS|publisher = [[Canada|Canadian Government]]| accessdate = 2009-04-04 | last= |quote=}}</ref>, nearly double its value in 2002. Canada chiefly imports petroleum and oil from Saudi Arabia, while exporting manufactured goods such as aircraft, cars, machinery and optical instruments.
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Serbia }}||<!--Date started-->1922
|
* Canada has an embassy in [[Belgrade]].<ref>[http://www.international.gc.ca/missions/serbia-serbie/  Canadian embassy in Belgrade]</ref> 
* Serbia has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and a general consulate in [[Toronto]] and 2 honorary consulates (in [[Montreal]] and [[Vancouver]]).<ref>[http://www.serbianembassy.ca/index_files/index_e.htm  Serbian embassy in Ottawa]</ref><ref>[http://gktoronto.com/  Serbian general consulate in Toronto]</ref>
* There are around 150,000 people of [[Serbian diaspora|Serbian descent]] living in Canada.
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/serbia-en.aspx  Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Serbia]
* [http://www.mfa.gov.rs/Policy/Bilaterala/Canada/index_e.html  Serbian Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Canada]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Singapore }}||<!--Date started-->1965
|
* Canada has a high commission in [[Singapore]].<ref>[http://geo.international.gc.ca/asia/singapore/menu-en.aspx  Canadian a high commission in Singapore]</ref>
* Singapore is represented in Canada through its embassy to the [[United Nations]] in [[New York City]] and through a general consulate in [[Vancouver]].
* Both countries are full members of the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] and of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]].
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/singapore-en.aspx  Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Singapore]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Slovakia }}||<!--Date started-->1993-01-01
|
* Canada is represented in Slovakia through its embassy in [[Prague]] ([[Czech Republic]]).<ref>[http://www.canada.cz/  Canadia embassy in Prague (also accredited to Slovakia)]</ref>
* Slovakia has an embassy in [[Ottawa]].<ref>[http://www.ottawa.mfa.sk/App/WCM/ZU/OttawaZU/main.nsf?Open  Slovak embassy in Ottawa]</ref>
* Both countries are full members of [[NATO]].
* There are around 100,000 people of [[Slovaks|Slovak descent]] living in Canada.
*[http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/slovak-republic-en.aspx  Canadia Ministry of Foreign affairs and Trade about the relation with Slovakia]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Slovenia }}||<!--Date started-->1993
|
* Canada recognized Slovenian independence in January 1992, and established diplomatic relations a year later. 
* Canada is represented through its embassy in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]], and through an honorary consulate in [[Ljubljana]].  
* Slovenia has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and a general consulate in [[Toronto]]. 
* Both countries are full members of [[NATO]].<ref>[http://ottawa.embassy.si/en   Slovenian embassy in Ottawa]</ref>
* There are more than 35,000 Slovenes who live in Canada.
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/slovenia-en.aspx   Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Slovenia]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|South Korea }}||<!--Date started-->1963-01-14||See [[Canada <U+2013> South Korea relations]]

* Canadian soldiers participated in the defense of South Korea during the [[Korean War]]. 
* Canada has an embassy in [[Seoul]].
* South Korea has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and 3 Consulate-Generals (in [[Montreal]], [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]]). 
* Both countries are full members of [[APEC]], [[OECD]] and the [[G20]].
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Spain }}||<!--Date started-->1920s
|
* Since [[1953]], Canada has an  embassy in [[Madrid]] and 2 honorary consulates in [[Barcelona]] and [[Malaga]].<ref>[http://www.international.gc.ca/missions/spain-espagne/menu.asp   Canadian embassy in Madrid]</ref> 
* Spain has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and 2 general consulates in [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]].<ref>[http://www.maec.es/Subwebs/Embajadas/Ottawa/en/Home/Paginas/Home.aspx  Spanish embassy in Ottawa]</ref>
* Both countries are full members of the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]], of [[NATO]] and of the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]]. 
* There are 213,000 people of [[Hispanic|Spanish descent]] living in Canada.
* In 1995, a [[Turbot War|fishing dispute]] between the two countries broke out after Canadian Officials boarded a Spanish vessel in international waters. 
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/spain-en.aspx  Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Spain]
* [http://www.maec.es/es/MenuPpal/Paises/ArbolPaises/Canada/Monografia/Documents/Canad<U+00E1>.pdf  Spanish Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation about relations with Canada (in Spanish only)]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Sweden }}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canada<U+2013>Sweden relations]]

Both countries have strong commitments to peacekeeping, UN reform, development assistance, environmental protection, sustainable development, and the promotion and protection of human rights.<ref>[http://geo.international.gc.ca/canada-europa/sweden/geo/sweden-bb-en.aspx Canada-Sweden Relations]</ref> In additional, there are [[Swedish Canadian|more than 300,000 Canadians of Swedish descent]].<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/highlights/ethnic/pages/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo=PR&Code=01&Data=Count&Table=2&StartRec=1&Sort=3&Display=All&CSDFilter=5000 Ethnic origins, 2006 counts, for Canada, provinces and territories]</ref> Canada has an [[embassy]] in [[Stockholm]] and two consulates in [[G<U+00F6>teborg]] and [[Malm<U+00F6>]]. Sweden has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and ten consulates in [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]], [[Fredericton]], [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], [[Montreal]], [[Quebec City]], [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], [[Toronto]], [[Vancouver]] and [[Winnipeg]].
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Switzerland }}||<!--Date started-->1945
|
* The first Swiss consulate opened in [[Montreal]] in [[1875]]. 
* Canada has an embassy in [[Berne]] and a consulate in [[Geneva]].<ref>[http://www.bern.gc.ca/  Canadian embassy in Bern]</ref>
* Switzerland has an embassy in [[Ottawa]], 3 consulates-general (in [[Montreal]], [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]]) and 4 consulate (in [[Calgary]], [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], [[Qu<U+00E9>bec]] and [[Winnipeg]]).<ref>[http://www.eda.admin.ch/eda/en/home/reps/nameri/vcan/canott.html   Swiss embassy in Ottawa]</ref>
* Both countries are full members of the [[Francophonie]].
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/switzerland-bb-en.aspx  Canadian Foreign Affairs and International Trade Department about relations with Switzerland]
* [http://www.eda.admin.ch/eda/en/home/reps/nameri/vcan/bilkan.html  Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs about relations with Canada]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Thailand }}||<!--Date started-->1947
|
* Canada has an embassy in [[Bangkok]] and a consulate in [[Chiang Mai]].<ref>[http://www.thailand.gc.ca  Embassy of Canada in Bangkok]</ref>
* Thailand has an embassy in [[Ottawa]], consulates general in [[Toronto]], [[Vancouver]], [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]] and [[Montreal]], and Thai Trade Centre Offices in [[Vancouver]] and [[Toronto]].<ref>[http://www.magma.ca/~thaiott/mainpage.htm   Royal Thai Embassy in Ottawa]</ref>
* Both countries are full members of the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] and Canada is a member of the [[ASEAN]] Regional Forum.
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/thailand-en.aspx  Canadian Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Thailand]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Tunisia }}||<!--Date started-->1957
|
* Since [[May]] [[1966]], Canada has an embassy in [[Tunis]]. 
* Since [[September]] [[1969]], Tunisia has an embassy in [[Ottawa]] and a consulate in [[Montreal]].
* Both countries are full members of the [[Francophonie]].
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/tunisia-en.aspx  Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Tunisia]
* [http://www.diplomatie.gov.tn/site/index.php?a=article&id=473  Tunisian Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Canada (in French only)]
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Turkey}}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canadian<U+2013>Turkish relations]]

* Canada has an embassy in Ankara.
* Turkey has an embassy in Ottawa.
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Ukraine }}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canada<U+2013>Ukraine relations]], [[Embassy of Ukraine in Ottawa]]

Diplomatic relations were established between Canada and Ukraine on January 27, 1992.<ref> For a detailed discussion of Canada's early diplomatic engagement with Canada, see Bohdan Kordan, "Canadian Ukrainian Relations: Articulating the Canadian Interest," in L. Hajda, ed. (1996), ''Ukraine in the World: Studies in the International Relations and Security Structure of a Newly Independent State''. Cambridge: Harvard University Press.</ref>  Canada opened its [[embassy]] in [[Kiev]]<ref>The capital of Ukraine (commonly "Kyiv" in English) is officially recognized by both the Canadian and Ukrainian governments as ''Kyiv'' in all English communications (although not in French).</ref> in April 1992, and the [[Embassy of Ukraine in Ottawa]] opened in October of that same year<ref name="ukremb">[http://www.mfa.gov.ua/canada/en/publication/content/7979.htm Embassy of Ukraine in Canada - Political Affairs]</ref>
, paid for mostly by donations from the Ukrainian-Canadian community.  Ukraine opened a [[consul general|consulate general]] in [[Toronto]] in 1993<ref name="ukremb">[http://www.mfa.gov.ua/canada/en/publication/content/7979.htm Embassy of Ukraine in Canada - Political Affairs],</ref> and announced plans to open another in [[Edmonton]] in 2008<ref name="edmjournal">[http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/local/story.html?id=26c438a2-4fad-4bc8-ad0e-0f17d70225fa&k=66349 Edmonton Journal]</ref>. Canada also has a [[consulate]] in [[L'viv]].

The main bilateral agreement signed between the two governments is the [[Treaty of Friendship|joint declaration of the "Special Partnership"]] between the two countries signed in 1994 and renewed in 2001.<ref name="ukremb"/>
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|United Kingdom }}||<!--Date started-->
|See [[Canada <U+2013> United Kingdom relations]], [[High Commission of the United Kingdom in Ottawa]], [[High Commission of Canada in London]], [[List of High Commissioners from the United Kingdom to Canada]], [[List of Canadian High Commissioners to the United Kingdom]]

[[London]] and [[Ottawa]] enjoy cooperative and intimate contact, which has grown deeper over the years; the two countries are related through history, the [[Commonwealth of Nations]], and their sharing of the same [[Head of State]] and [[monarch]].
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|United States }}||<!--Date started-->
|
[[File:Barack Obama meets Stephen Harper.jpg|Canadian Prime Minister Harper (right) and U.S. President Obama meet in Ottawa in February 2009|thumb|right|300px]]
See [[Canada<U+2013>United States relations]], [[Embassy of the United States in Ottawa]],  [[Embassy of Canada in Washington]], [[United States Ambassador to Canada]], [[List of Canadian ambassadors to the United States]]

Relations between Canada and the United States span more than two centuries, marked by a shared [[British colonization of the Americas|British colonial heritage]], conflict during the early years of the [[United States|U.S.]], and the eventual development of one of the most successful international relationships in the modern world. The most serious breach in the relationship was the [[War of 1812]], which saw an American invasion of then [[British North America]] and counter invasions from British-Canadian forces. The border was demilitarized after the war and, apart from minor raids, has remained peaceful. Military collaboration began during the [[World Wars]] and continued throughout the Cold War, despite [[Canada|Canadian]] doubts about certain American policies. A high volume of trade and migration between the U.S. and Canada has generated closer ties, despite continued Canadian fears of being overwhelmed by its neighbor, which is ten times larger in population, wealth and debt.<ref> James Tagg reports that Canadian university students have a profound fear that "Canadian culture, and likely Canadian sovereignty, will be overwhelmed." Tagg, "'And, We Burned down the White House, Too': American History, Canadian Undergraduates, and Nationalism," ''The History Teacher,'' Vol. 37, No. 3 (May, 2004), pp. 309-334  [http://www.jstor.org/stable/1555672 in JSTOR];  J. L. Granatstein. ''Yankee Go Home: Canadians and Anti-Americanism'' (1997)</ref>

Canada and the United States are currently the world's largest trading partners, share [[Canada <U+2013> United States border|the world's longest shared border]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelongestlistofthelongeststuffatthelongestdomainnameatlonglast.com/long263.html|title=The world's longest border|accessdate=2008-04-01}}</ref> and have significant interoperability within the defense sphere. 
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Uruguay }}||<!--Date started-->1953-01||See [[Canada<U+2013>Uruguay relations]]

* Canada has an embassy in [[Montevideo]].
* Uruguay has an embassy in [[Ottawa]], 2 general consulate in [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]], and an honorary consulate in [[Vancouver]]. 
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Venezuela }}||<!--Date started-->||See [[Canada<U+2013>Venezuela relations]]

In February 1948 there was a Canadian [[Consulate General]] in [[Caracas]] and a Venezuelan Consulate General in [[Montreal]]. In that year the Venezuelan Consul General, on behalf of the government of Venezuela, made a [[rapprochement]] with Canada in order to open direct diplomatic representations between the two countries;<ref> ''Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada'' [http://www.international.gc.ca/department/history/dcer/details-en.asp?intRefid=11327 Documents on Canadian External Relations] Accessed 17 December 2007 </ref> but the Canadian government delayed the opening of a diplomatic mission in Venezuela because of the lack of enough suitable personnel for the manning of a Canadian mission in Venezuela and the impossibility of Canada beginning a representation in Venezuela in that year without considering a policy of expansion of Canadian representation abroad.<ref>''Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada'' [http://www.international.gc.ca/department/history/dcer/details-en.asp?intRefid=11328 Documents on Canadian External Relations] Accessed 17 December 2007 </ref>

In the interest of protecting Canadian trade with Venezuela and considering the difficulties for business in being without a Canadian representation in Caracas, Canada was pushed to accept the Venezuelan offer of exchanging diplomatic missions.<ref>''Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada'' [http://www.international.gc.ca/department/history/dcer/details-en.asp?intRefid=3536   Documents on Canadian External Relations] Accessed 17 December 2007 </ref> Finally Canada elevated the former office of the Canadian Consulate General in Caracas to the category of embassy in 1953.<ref>''The Canadian Embassy in Venezuela'' [http://geo.international.gc.ca/latin-america/caracas/geo/venezuela-bb-en.aspx  Bilateral Relations] Accessed 17 December 2007</ref>

On the other hand Venezuela established an embassy in Canada in 1952.<ref>''Embassy of Venezuela in Canada'' [http://www.misionvenezuela.org/ingles/embajada.htm] Accessed 18 December 2007</ref> Since then there have been good commercial relations between the two countries, especially in technology, oil and gas industry, telecommunications and others.
|--valign="top"
|{{flag|Vietnam}}||<!--Date started-->1973-08-21
|
* Since [[1994]], Canada has an embassy in [[Hanoi]] and since [[1997]] a general consulate in [[Ho Chi Minh City]].<ref>[http://geo.international.gc.ca/asia/vietnam/menu-en.asp  Canadian embassy in Hanoi]</ref>
* Vietnam has an embassy in [[Ottawa]].
* Both countries are full members of the [[Francophonie]] and of the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]]. 
* There are 152,000 people of [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese descent]] living in Canada.
* [http://geo.international.gc.ca/cip-pic/geo/vietnam-en.aspx  Canadian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Trade about relations with Vietnam]
* [http://www.mofa.gov.vn/en/cn_vakv/america/nr040819113843  Vietnamese Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Canada]
